  "prompt": "Why do jain sadhus do not wear clothes?",
  "response": "Jain sadhus, particularly those belonging to the Digambara sect, may choose not to wear clothes due to their interpretation of the Jain principles of non-attachment and asceticism. The term \"Digambara\" itself means \"sky-clad,\" symbolizing the practice of renouncing all worldly possessions, including clothing, to achieve spiritual purity and liberation from the cycle of rebirth (samsara).\n\nThis practice is rooted in the belief that attachment to material possessions, including clothes, can lead to desires and distractions, hindering one's spiritual progress. By going unclothed, Digambara monks emphasize the importance of shedding all forms of attachment and living a life of simplicity and humility. It's important to note that this approach is not adopted by all Jains; those from the Svetambara sect, for example, do wear simple white clothing but still adhere to the principles of non-attachment and asceticism in other ways.",
